Q: C++ Write a program that prompts the user to enter a person&#39;s date of birth in numeric form (Throw/Catch) A: <p>In 2025 (and later), with C++20 or later, this is a simpler solution to this problem:</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>#include &lt;chrono&gt;
#include &lt;format&gt;
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;sstream&gt;
#include &lt;stdexcept&gt;

int
main()
{
    try
    {
        using namespace std;
        chrono::year_month_day birthday;
        cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Enter birthday: mm/dd/yyyy : &quot;;
        string line;
        getline(cin, line);
        if (cin.fail())
            throw std::runtime_error(&quot;failed to get line from user&quot;);
        istringstream in{std::move(line)};
        in &gt;&gt; parse(&quot;%m/%d/%Y&quot;, birthday);
        if (in.fail())
            throw std::runtime_error('\&quot;' + line + '\&quot;' +
                &quot; is not a valid date of the form mm/dd/yyyy&quot;);
        cout &lt;&lt; format(&quot;{:%B %e, %Y}&quot;, birthday) &lt;&lt; '\n';
    }
    catch (std::exception const&amp; e)
    {
        std::cerr &lt;&lt; e.what() &lt;&lt; '\n';
    }
}

</code></pre>
<p>The <code>&lt;chrono&gt;</code> library has the data structures, parsing, formatting and error checking to completely address this issue.  This solution includes checking for invalid dates, even for leap years.  This is done under <code>std::chrono::parse</code>, and detected by the <code>in.fail()</code> expression.  This solution also includes the month number to month name translation.</p>
<p>More complex checking could tease apart exactly which part of the input is invalid.  This could be any of:</p>
<ul>
<li>Improper delimiter's (<code>/</code>).</li>
<li>Out of bound year (the <code>&lt;chrono&gt;</code> library considers years outside of the bound [-32767, 32767] to be an error).</li>
<li>Out of bound month ([1, 12]).</li>
<li>Out of bound day in combination with the month and year, including leap year rules.</li>
</ul>
<p>The parsing is done from an <code>istringstream</code> only for the purpose of improving the error message by including the user input in the error message.  If that feature is not desired, one could <code>parse</code> directly from <code>cin</code>.</p>
<p>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proleptic_Gregorian_calendar" rel="nofollow noreferrer">proleptic Gregorian calendar</a> is assumed.</p>

Q: Synchronized method and access with another thread A: <p>When a thread accesses a synchronized method of an object, no other thread can access that method or any other synchronized method of the same object (if they are not synchronized). Let's see how this works:</p>
<pre><code>public class Product {

     // used as a lock that enables or disables entry into
     // the *while* loop that will invoke **wait**
   boolean bloqued = false;

   synchronized void add() {
      System.out.println( &quot; in the door of  add&quot; );

      try {

           // depending on the state of **blocked**, either the
           // method's statements will be executed, or it will
           // enter the *while* loop to call **wait** and remain
           // waiting for a **notify()**.
         while( bloqued ) {
            wait();
         }

           // if we access the statements, we assign the value
           // “true” to **bloqued**, so that the other threads
           // are forced to enter the *while* loop.
         bloqued = true;
         Thread.sleep( 4000 );
      }
      catch( InterruptedException e ) {
         throw new RuntimeException( e );
      }
      System.out.println( &quot;Finished add&quot; );

        // we return to the unlocked state
      bloqued = false;
      notifyAll();
   }

   void popo() {
      System.out.println( &quot;  exec and Finished not syncronized popo()&quot; );
   }

   synchronized void reduce() {
      System.out.println( &quot; in the door of reduce&quot; );
      try {
         while( bloqued ) {
            wait();
         }
         bloqued = true;
      }
      catch( InterruptedException e ) {
         throw new RuntimeException( e );
      }
      System.out.println( &quot;Finished reduce&quot; );
      bloqued = false;
      notifyAll();
   }
}

public class MYThread extends Thread {

   Product pro;
   int a = 0;

   MYThread( Product p, int x ) {
      pro = p;
      a = x;
   }

   @Override
   public void run() {
      if( a == 0 ) {
         pro.add();
      }
      else if( a == 1 ) {
         pro.popo();
      }
      else {
         pro.reduce();
      }
   }
}

public class Main {

   void ini() {
      Product product = new Product();
      MiThread b = new MiThread( product, 0 ); // add
      MiThread a = new MiThread( product, 1 ); // popo
      MiThread c = new MiThread( product, 2 ); // reduce
      b.start();
      c.start();
      a.start();
   }

   public static void main( String[] args ) {
      new Main().ini();
   }
}
</code></pre>
<p>As you can see, the execution prints something like:</p>
<pre><code> in the door of  add
  exec and Finished not syncronized popo()
</code></pre>
<p>and after the 4 seconds that the <strong>add</strong> method “takes” to execute, it prints:</p>
<pre><code>Finished add
 in the door of reduce
Finished reduce
</code></pre>
<p><a href="https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/concurrency/syncmeth.html" rel="nofollow noreferrer">More info here</a></p>
